<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06188112 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06188112 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  PROFESSIONAL; BASEBALL; SAN-FRANCISCO  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Roger Craig said he calls team meetings only at the beginning of springtraining and before the start of the regular season.;    On Friday, however,the Giants manager called a team gathering, and it wasn't to pat his playerson their backs.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Sports  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  GIANTS MEET TO CLEAR AIR ABOUT WRITER'S ALLEGATIONS  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Giants Notes  </MEMO><TEXT>     Craig responded to a San Francisco Chronicle column by Lowell Cohn, whowrote that unidentified Giants players were upset about alleged specialtreatment given to slugger Kevin Mitchell. Cohn also expressed doubts aboutCraig's managing.;    &quot;If I let that thing slide, I might as well pack up mycase and go home,&quot; said Craig, who didn't hold anything back.;    The Giantsmanager said he asked his players to confront him or Mitchell if they madethose comments.;    &quot;Tell (Mitchell) what you think; be a man and give him ananswer,&quot; Craig said. &quot;This is the last place for finger pointing.&quot;;    As forfavoring Mitchell, Craig said the outfielder &quot;has some private things he's hadto attend to, and I'm not going to tell you what they are.&quot;;    Mitchell saidhe was unaware of the story until he arrived at the ballpark.;    &quot;If theperson was any kind of man, he would come to me,&quot; said Mitchell, who added hewas surprised by accusations concerning his non-participation in stretchingworkouts.;    Mitchell said he usually conducts his pregame stretchingworkouts under the supervision of a therapist because of the condition of hisleft knee, which underwent surgery June 4. Craig said the team's pregamestretching isn't mandatory.;    &quot;It seems like when things go bad, they pointto me as the scapegoat,&quot; Mitchell said.;    Relief pitcher Jeff Brantley saidhe spoke at the meeting, but only to let his teammates know that he and Craighad settled their differences over a recent game in which he was upset bybeing pulled.;    &quot;It was up front,&quot; Brantley said. &quot;That's the way you dothings.&quot;; ETC.: John Burkett (4-5) will start Sunday's game for the Giants,Craig said. Burkett will be throwing on three days' rest. However, he threwonly 87 pitches in five innings in his last start, against Houston. Hereplaces Bud Black, who is sidelined by tendinitis in his left elbow.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  MARK GONZALES, Mercury News Staff Writer  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  San Francisco  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910706  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Saturday  </DAY><MONTH>  July  </MONTH><PG.COL>  5F  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  365  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Saturday July 6, 199100188112,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>